{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0d1ec5a6-8396-4718-9f03-fcb4ac64de6a","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads, aligning them with your current SDK. This is what you need after an SDK update.\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — reinstalls the *same* versions already recorded; it fixes corrupted or missing files but won't pull newer packages.\n\nSince the SDK moved forward and your workload packages are stale, `update` will fetch the matching MAUI bits. After that, clean and rebuild:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet clean\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf the build still fails, check `dotnet workload list` to confirm `maui` (or `maui-windows`, etc.) is present.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6b254c67-8357-4cc4-80c6-2cfed11c0454","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix a .NET MAUI build issue after an SDK update. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search files or run commands.","outputTokens":250,"requestId":"503A:1CB4B6:1B3A2BE:1E3819A:69FA8F72"},"id":"7d031ac0-005b-482f-aa1b-4ea58746e40a","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:46:49.819Z","parentId":"958663d3-a1c3-4620-9582-6bd4f58b7654"}
